                Export JSON
              </button>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>

      </div>

    </div>

    <RelatedTools currentSlug="accelerometer-viewer" />
  </section>

  <!-- SEO Content Article -->
  <section
    class="max-w-[760px] w-full mx-auto px-4 pb-12 flex flex-col gap-8 text-slate"
    aria-labelledby="about-tool-heading"
  >
    <article class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <h2
        id="about-tool-heading"
        class="font-display font-semibold text-xl sm:text-2xl text-primary tracking-tight"
      >
        Free Online Accelerometer Viewer & Logger
      </h2>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        An <strong>accelerometer</strong> is an essential sensor that measures proper accelerationâ€”the rate of velocity change of an object relative to its own rest frame. If you have ever wondered <strong>what is an accelerometer</strong>, it is the technology that detects motion, tilt, shock, and vibration. According to the scientific <strong>accelerometer definition</strong>, these devices measure the force of acceleration, which can be static (such as the continuous gravitational pull of the Earth) or dynamic (such as sudden motion, drops, or impacts). This web application serves as a browser-based <strong>accelerometer logger</strong>, allowing you to test and analyze your device's built-in <strong>accelerometer sensor</strong> in real time.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Our tool utilizes standard browser APIs to access your hardware motion sensors safely and securely inside your browser's local sandbox. Whether you are troubleshooting a mobile sensor, testing a web app, or conducting a basic physics experiment, this online viewer plots incoming movement signals immediately. You can switch between gravity-compensated linear motion or raw gravity-inclusive modes, track maximum peaks on all coordinate planes, and export logged samples as CSV or JSON files.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        How Does an Accelerometer Work?
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        If you want to know <strong>how does an accelerometer work</strong>, the answer lies in miniaturized electrical engineering. Modern mobile devices use micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS) sensors. Inside a MEMS <strong>accelerometer sensor</strong>, a tiny silicon seismic mass is suspended by micro-springs. When your device moves, inertia shifts this mass. The shifting movement alters the distance between the microscopic mass and fixed plates, changing the electrical capacitance.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        The sensor's internal circuitry measures this capacitive change and translates it into a digital signal. This process explains <strong>how does accelerometer sensor work</strong> to produce high-frequency X, Y, and Z readings. In industrial environments, piezoelectric crystals are often used instead; physical force squeezes the crystal, generating a small electric charge proportional to the acceleration.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        Accelerometer: What Does It Do?
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        When asking "<strong>accelerometer: what does it do</strong>?", the answer spans countless industries. In smartphones, it automatically rotates your screen, detects shake gestures, and tracks steps for health monitoring. In vehicle safety, it detects severe deceleration to trigger airbag inflation. In structural engineering, it monitors the swaying of skyscrapers and bridges.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        So, <strong>what does an accelerometer measure</strong>? It measures acceleration forces across three spatial axes. By using a <strong>3 axis accelerometer</strong>, software can isolate motion on the X (lateral), Y (longitudinal), and Z (vertical) axes. This multi-axis layout is critical for mapping spatial motion, calculating total vector magnitude, and recording impact intensity.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        How to Measure Vibration Using an Accelerometer
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Vibration monitoring is a primary industrial use for these sensors. To measure vibration, the sensor is mounted securely to a machine or surface. By monitoring acceleration over time at a high refresh rate, engineers can isolate peak frequency responses and detect mechanical faults, misalignment, or wear. Using our free online logger, you can record these vibration cycles and export the raw raw data directly to standard spreadsheet software for further numerical analysis.
      </p>
    </article>

